word.description: Add spacing between a short equation and the preceding text. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
Add spacing between an equation and the preceding text. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
The name given to the abstract header; defaults to "Abstract".
Adds an entry to the specified list or table.
The return address, as it should appear on the letter and the envelope.
Adds text (or formatting commands) directly to the file that generates the specified list or table.
Adds "number" to the current value of "counter".
Adds "length" to the length command "length_name".
Add a vertical space of size "length".
Allow page breaks to occur in math formulas.
Allow page breaks to occur in math formulas. "num" is value 0 to 4 describing the ease with which page breaks are added.
Causes the current value of a specified counter to be printed in uppercase alphabetic characters.
Causes the current value of a specified counter to be printed in lowercase alphabetic characters.
Prints the name used by a \seealso command.
Prints the text used to separate multiple author names in the \author command.
Changes the way sectional units are numbered so that information after the command is considered part of the appendix.
The name given to an appendix; defaults to "Appendix".
Causes the current value of a specified counter to be printed in Arabic numbers.
Value is half of the pace between columns in the array environment. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
The thickness of line strokes in the array and tabular environments. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
Multiplier to adjust the spacing between rows in a table; default is 1. Value is modified with the \renewcommand command.
Defines commands to be executed at the beginning of the document environment.
Defines commands to be executed at the end of the document environment.
Defines commands to be executed upon the completion of the current class file being read.
Defines commands to be executed upon the completion of the current package file being read.

Declares the author(s), where names is a list of authors separated by \and commands. Use \\ to separate lines within a single author's entry - for example, to give the author's institution or address.
In the book class, disables chapter numbering to prepare to include supplementary content (bibliography, etc.).
Specifies the minimum space between the bottom of two successive lines in a paragraph. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
A multiplier that scales the value of \baselineskip. Value is modified with the \renewcommand command (updated value takes effect after the next font size change).
The start of environment "env", which is later terminated by the \end command. Many declaration commands can be used as the argument value, as well.
The start of environment abstract.
The start of environment align. Switches to math mode and allows equations to be aligned using "&" characters. Equation lines are numbered (use align* environment to disable numbering).
The start of environment align. Switches to math mode and allows equations to be aligned using "&" characters. Equation lines are not numbered (use align environment to enable numbering).
The start of environment alignat. The alignat environment is the same as align, except there is no spacing between columns by default.
The start of environment aligned. Like the align environment, but used when math mode is already initiated.

The start of environment aligned. Like the align environment, but used when math mode is already initiated. The argument "pos" determines how the contents are aligned relative to surrounding text ("t" for top, "b" for bottom, default is "c" for center).

The start of environment array. The array environment is used to generating matrices and vectors. The argument col consists of a formatting character for each column in the matrix to describe text justification ("l" for left, "c" for center, "r" for right).

The start of environment array. The array environment is used to generating matrices and vectors. The argument "pos" determines how the contents are aligned relative to surrounding text ("t" for top, "b" for bottom, default is "c" for center). The argument col consists of a formatting character for each column in the matrix to describe text justification ("l" for left, "c" for center, "r" for right).
The start of environment center. Each line of text is centered. Use "\\" to terminate a line.
The start of environment alltt (requires alltt package). Text is printed as it is formatted in the source document, including the preservation of whitespace, newlines, and special characters.
The start of environment bmatrix. A matrix enclosed in square brackets.
The start of environment Bmatrix. A matrix enclosed in curly braces.
The start of environment cases. Individual lines of the equation are each left justified, but the entire block of lines is centered.
The start of environment description. An indented list of labelled items. The \item command is used to provide the label text.
The start of environment displaymath. Switch to displayed math mode to put an equation on its own line. Equivalent to "\[".
The start of environment document. Appears after the preamble, to open the main contents of the document.
The start of environment enumerate. A numbered, indented list of labelled items. The \item command is used to provide the label text.

The start of environment eqnarray. Display a multiline formula in the form of a 3-column table. Each line of the formula is displayed with a sequential equation number, unless the \nonumber command is used.
The start of environment eqnarray*. The start of environment eqnarray. Display a multiline formula in the form of a 3-column table. No equation numbers are dislayed.

The start of environment falign. Switches to math mode and allows equations to be aligned using "&" characters. Equation lines are numbered. Spacing between columns is added as needed so that the width of the block fills the line.
The start of environment figure. Adds a floating figure.
The start of environment figure. Adds a floating figure. Positioning is determined by the "loc" argument.
The start of environment figure. Adds a floating figure, which fills both columns in a 2-column page format.
The start of environment figure. Adds a floating figure, which fills both columns in a 2-column page format. Positioning is determined by the "loc" argument.
The start of environment filecontents. The contents of the environment are written to the file indicated by "filename", with initial comment lines indicating the source of the contents.
The start of environment filecontents. The contents of the environment are written to the file indicated by "filename".
The start of environment flushleft. Each line of text is left-justified, but is not aligned on the right side.
The start of environment flushright. Each line of text is right-justified, but is not aligned on the left side.
The start of environment gather. Switches to math mode and individually centers each equation line. Equation lines are numbered (use gather* environment to disable numbering).
The start of environment gather*. Switches to math mode and individually centers each equation line. Equation lines are not numbered (use gather environment to enable numbering).
The start of environment gathered. When already in math mode, individually centers each contained equation line.

The start of environment gathered. When already in math mode, individually centers each contained equation line. The argument "pos" determines the vertical alignment of the contained equations relative to surrounding text ("t" for top, "b" for bottom", default is center).
The start of environment itemize. An indented list of bulleted items. The \item command is used to declare each item.
The start of environment letter. The beginning of a letter document. The name and address is included in the "recipient" argument.

The start of environment list. Defines a list which can be customized by the "label" and "declarations" arguments. The "label" argument includes text and commands that determine how item labels appear. The "declarations" argument includes formatting commands.
The start of environment longtable, part of the longtable package. The longtable environment supports all of the commands used in the tabular environment, but its tables can span multiple pages.
The start of environment lrbox. Used for drawing a box around content.
The start of environment math. Switches to inline math mode, allowing formulas to appear inline with surrounding content. "\(" and "$" can also be used as short forms of this command.
The start of environment matrix. Include a matrix while in math mode; the matrix is not enclosed by any brackets or braces.
The start of environment minipage. Allows content to be formatted to fill only a small area on a page, with the region defined by the arguments.
The start of environment minipage. Allows content to be formatted to fill only a small area on a page, with the region defined by the arguments.

The start of environment multicols, part of the multicol package. Displays text in the number of columns indicated by the "num_cols" argument. The contents of the columns are balanced on the final page (use the multicols* environment for unbalanced).

The start of environment multicols, part of the multicol package. Displays text in the number of columns indicated by the "num_cols" argument. The contents of the "header" argument appear across all of the columns. If the amount of space left on a page is less than the "pre_space" argument, then the columns are started on the next page. The contents of the columns are balanced on the final page (use the multicols* environment for unbalanced).

The start of environment multicols*, part of the multicol package. Displays text in the number of columns indicated by the "num_cols" argument. The contents of the columns are not balanced on the final page (use the multicols environment for balanced).

The start of environment multicols*, part of the multicol package. Displays text in the number of columns indicated by the "num_cols" argument. The contents of the "header" argument appear across all of the columns. If the amount of space left on a page is less than the "pre_space" argument, then the columns are started on the next page. The contents of the columns are not balanced on the final page (use the multicols* environment for balanced).

The start of environment multiline. This environment switches to math mode and is used for displaying a single equation that appears across multiple lines. Shows an equation number (use multiline* to hide number).

The start of environment multiline. This environment switches to math mode and is used for displaying a single equation that appears across multiple lines. Does not show an equation number (use multiline to show number).
The start of environment note, applicable to a document with the "slides" class. Displays a note for the current slide.
The start of environment overlay, applicable to a document with the "slides" class. Used for content that is to appear on top of the current slide.

The start of environment picture. Pictures define a canvas on which drawing commands can print. The "width" and "height" arguments specify the dimensions of the canvas, in the unit previously specified with the \unitlength command.

The start of environment picture. Pictures define a canvas on which drawing commands can print. The "width" and "height" arguments specify the dimensions of the canvas, in the unit previously specified with the \unitlength command.
The start of environment pmatrix. A matrix enclosed in round parentheses.
The start of environment quotation. In a quotation environment, text is indented on both the right and the left. The beginnings of new paragraphs are given further indentation.

The start of environment quote. In a quote environment, text is indented on both the right and the left. The beginning of a new paragraph is given additional line spacing from the preceding paragraph..
The start of environment slide, applicable to a document with the "slides" class or the "seminar" class. Defines a new slide.
The start of environment sloppypar. In this environment, word spacing has additional flexibility, reducing the amount of hyphenation.
The start of environment split. Used within an existing math environment, for a single equation that should be split across multiple lines.
The start of environment subarray. The argument "position" may be "c" to center array elements or "l" for left justification. The "contents" are array elements separated by "\\".
The start of environment subequations. Number contained equations using the current equation number followed by sequential letters (e.g. 3a, 3b, 3c, etc.).
The start of environment tabbing. The tabbing environment allows for special commands to create and use tab stops.
The start of environment table. Insert a floating table into the document.
The start of environment table. Insert a floating table into the document. The argument "loc" determines table positioning.
The start of environment table*. Insert a floating table into the document. The table will span both columns when the twocolumn option is enabled.
The start of environment table*. Insert a floating table into the document. The argument "loc" determines table positioning. The table will span both columns when the twocolumn option is enabled.

The start of environment tabular. Insert a table into the document. Column entries are separated by "&", and each row is terminated by "\\". The argument "cols" consists of a formatting character describing each column ("l" for left-justified, "r" for right-justified, "c" for centered, p{w} for a column of width "w").

The start of environment tabular. Insert a table into the document. Column entries are separated by "&", and each row is terminated by "\\". The argument "pos" describes how the table is vertically aligned relative to surrounding text ("t" for top, "b" for bottom, default is center). The argument "cols" consists of a formatting character describing each column ("l" for left-justified, "r" for right-justified, "c" for centered, p{w} for a column of width "w").

The start of environment tabular*. Insert a table into the document. Column entries are separated by "&", and each row is terminated by "\\". The argument "width" is the total width of the table. The argument "cols" consists of a formatting character describing each column ("l" for left-justified, "r" for right-justified, "c" for centered, p{w} for a column of width "w").

The start of environment tabular*. Insert a table into the document. Column entries are separated by "&", and each row is terminated by "\\". The argument "width" is the total width of the table. The argument "pos" describes how the table is vertically aligned relative to surrounding text ("t" for top, "b" for bottom, default is center). The argument "cols" consists of a formatting character describing each column ("l" for left-justified, "r" for right-justified, "c" for centered, p{w} for a column of width "w").

The start of environment thebibliography. Used to include a bibliography in the document, with the \bibitem command for each entry. The "indent_label" argument is a text value, the width of which is used as the indentation for bibliography entries.
The start of environment theindex. Used to include a keyword index in the document.
Begin an environment of type "theorem_type", which has previously been defined by the \newtheorem command.
Begin an environment of type "theorem_type", which has previously been defined by the \newtheorem command. The "theorem_title" argument allows for an optional title to be provided.
The start of environment titlepage. Insert a title page into the document; the title page does not have a page number.
The start of environment trivlist. Insert a simple list where items do not have labels.
The start of environment verbatim. Text is printed as it is formatted in the source document, including the preservation of whitespace, newlines, and special characters.

The start of environment verbatim. Text is printed as it is formatted in the source document, including the preservation of whitespace, newlines, and special characters. Space characters are made visible by printing them as "Ë½".
The start of environment verse.
The start of environment vmatrix. A matrix enclosed by vertical lines.
The start of environment Vmatrix. A matrix enclosed by double vertical lines.
In math mode, set the vertical space below a display style math formula, if the following paragraph does not overlap the fomula part. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
In math mode, set the vertical space below a display style math formula, if the following paragraph does not overlap the fomula part. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
The font series attribute that is set by the \bfseries command.
Switch to the bold version of the current font.
Add a new entry to a bibliography. The "key" argument is referenced in other commands to cite the entry.

Add a new entry to a bibliography. The "label" argument is used to identify the entry in the bibliograph (if omitted, an incrementing number is used). The "key" argument is referenced in other commands to cite the entry.
Used to produce a bibliography using the contents of BibTeX files. The argument "files" is a comma-delimited list of references to BibTeX files.
Select a style for a BibTeX-based bibliography.
The name given to the bibliography; defaults to "Bibliography".

Produces an enlarged bracket symbol (smaller than \Big), where "bracket_symbol" is one of:
( [ \{ | / ) ] \} \| \backslash \lfloor \lceil \langle \uparrow \downarrow \updownarrow \rfloor \rceil \rangle \Uparrow \Downarrow \Updownarrow

Produces a large bracket symbol (larger than \big, smaller than \bigg), where "bracket_symbol" is one of:
( [ \{ | / ) ] \} \| \backslash \lfloor \lceil \langle \uparrow \downarrow \updownarrow \rfloor \rceil \rangle \Uparrow \Downarrow \Updownarrow

Produces a large bracket symbol (larger than \Big, smaller than Bigg), where "bracket_symbol" is one of:
( [ \{ | / ) ] \} \| \backslash \lfloor \lceil \langle \uparrow \downarrow \updownarrow \rfloor \rceil \rangle \Uparrow \Downarrow \Updownarrow

Produces the largest bracket symbol (larger than \bigg), where "bracket_symbol" is one of:
( [ \{ | / ) ] \} \| \backslash \lfloor \lceil \langle \uparrow \downarrow \updownarrow \rfloor \rceil \rangle \Uparrow \Downarrow \Updownarrow
Inserts a large amount of vertical spacing, determined by the value of the \bigskipamount command.
The amount of vertical spacing inserted by the \bigskip command. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
Insert a binomial expression into a math formula.
Insert the symbol "mod" into a formula.
Switch to math mode with a bold-face font.
Displays "symbol" in a bold-face font.
Can be defined using \renewcommand to execute a set of custom commands before the page-bottom floats.
The maximum proportion of a page that may be taken by the page-bottom floats. Value is set with \renewcommand.
Displays "formula" in a box.
In the figure or table float environments, produces a caption with the specified text.
In the figure or table float environments, produces a caption with the specified text. The "short_form" argument is what appears in the table/figure list. If omitted, it defaults to "text".
Switch to a different language for various section titles. For example, "language" may be "german", producing the command \captionsgerman.
Produce "cc:" copies in the letter document class. The "names_list" argument is a list of names being addressed (names are often separated by "\\").
The text label to be printed by the \cc command; defaults to "cc".
Produces a vertically centered ellipsis.
Center the remaining lines of text in the current environment.
Place "text" on a new line and center it.
Produces a fraction, which can have nested \cfrac commands in the numerator or denominator.

Produces a fraction, which can have nested \cfrac commands in the numerator or denominator. The argument "pos" determines the position of the numerator ("l" for left, "r" for right, default is center).
Start a new chapter with the specified "title". A chapter number is displayed before the title.
Start a new chapter with the specified "title". A chapter number is displayed before the title. The argument "short_title" is used in the table of contents and the page header.
Start a new chapter with the specified "title". A chapter number is not displayed, and the chapter does not appear in the table of contents.
The name given to a chapter; defaults to "Chapter".
In the picture environment, produce a circle with the specified diameter.
In the picture environment, produces a solid circle with the specified diameter.
The key_list argument is a list of citation keys. This command generates an in-text citation to the references associated with the keys in key_list.

The key_list argument is a list of citation keys. This command generates an in-text citation to the references associated with the keys in key_list. The optional text argument will appear after the citation, i.e. \cite[p. 2]{knuth} might produce [Knuth, p. 2].
Part of the natbib package. Inserts a parenthetical citation.
Part of the natbib package. Inserts a parenthetical citation, and allows additional notes in the parentheses at the beginning and end.
Part of the natbib package. Inserts a parenthetical citation, and allows additional notes in the parentheses at the beginning and end.
Part of the natbib package. Inserts an in-text citation (without parentheses).
All unprocessed floats are displayed. Additional content is not displayed until the next odd-numbered page after the floats (right-hand page in a book).
All unprocessed floats are displayed. Additional content is not displayed until the next page after the floats.
In the tabular environment, draw a horizontal line from the beginning of column "n" to the end of column "m".
Signifies the end of the main content in the letter environment. The "regards" argument is for the closing text.
Set the current text color to the color with the specified name.
Set the current text color to the color with the specified model and specs. For example, the model may be "rgb", and the specs may be "1.0, 0.0, 0.0" for red.
The "text" argument is displayed, having its text colored with the specified name.
The "text" argument is displayed, having its text colored with the specified model and specs. For example, the model may be "rgb", and the specs may be "1.0, 0.0, 0.0" for red.
The amount of spacing between columns in two-column page formatting. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
The width of the separator line between columns in two-column page formatting. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
The name given to the table of contents; defaults to "Contents".

In the picture environment, draw a box with a dashed border. "dash" is the length of the dashes; "width" and "height" are the dimensions of the box; and "pos" is a combination of "l" or "r" and "t" or "b" (left or right; top or bottom), indicating the position of the box. The "text" argument is the contents of the box.
Set "date_text" as the value to be printed where the current date is printed (like on the title page). Without this command, the current date is system time.
Specifies how the \today command is formatted; for example, \dateenglish.
Insert a binomial expression into a math formula; size is determined by \displaystyle.
Can be defined using \renewcommand to execute a set of custom commands after a two-column float at the top of a page.
The maximum proportion of a float page that can be filled with two-column floats. Value is modified with the \renewcommand command.
The amount of spacing between adjacent two-column floats. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
The amount of spacing between a two-column float and the following text content. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
The maximum proportion of a page that can be filled with two-column floats. Value is modified with the \renewcommand command.
Add a triple-dot over math variable "x".
Add a quadruple-dot over math variable "x".
Define a new color named "name" with the specified model and specs. For example, the model may be "rgb", and the specs may be "1.0, 0.0, 0.0" for red.
A length value representing the distance between the baseline and bottom of a box.
Displays a fraction in a math formula like \frac, but uses \displaystyle to determine size.
Used in the middle of the word to specify hyphenation. If the word is hyphenated, "before" is displayed at the end of the line while "after" starts the next line. Otherwise, "without" is displayed.
Insert a page break into a math formula.
Specifies a location in a math formula where a page break can occur. The "num" argument is a value 0 to 4 that indicates how agressive page breaking should be (4 forces a break).
Specifies that the font size for displayed formulas should be used.
Specifies the type of document. The "class" argument is usually article, report, book, letter, or slides.
Specifies the type of document. The "class" argument is usually article, report, book, letter, or slides.
Specifies the type of document. The "class" argument is usually article, report, book, letter, or slides. The "version" argument is a date formatted yyyy/mm/dd.
Extra space in the current line is filled with dots, so that preceding text appears left-justified, and following text appears right-justified.
Displays an ellipsis. Or in math mode with the amsmath package, places continuation dots whose height is determined by the following symbol.
Dots for a following binary operator.
Dots placed at the height of a comma.
Dots placed at the center height of an integral sign.
Dots for symbolizing multiplication.
Part of the fancybox package. Displays a double-lined box around text.
The spacing between double lines in the tabular and array environments. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
Toggles to and from an emphasized font, normally displayed in italics.
Displays "text" in an emphasized font, normally italics.
Produces the enclosures section in a letter document class.
The name given to the enclosures label; defaults to "encl".
Terminate an environment; should match a previous \begin command.
Part of the longtable package. Signifies the end of content to appear in the table header on the first page only.
Part of the longtable package. Signifies the end of content to appear in the table footer on each page except the last.
Part of the longtable package. Signifies the end of content to appear in the table header on each page except the first.
Part of the longtable package. Signifies the end of content to appear in the table footer on the last page.
Increase \textheight by "size" for the current page only.
Increase \textheight by "size" for the current page only. Additional spacing between lines on the page is removed to allow more text to fit on the page.
Ensure that math mode is enabled so that "math_commands" can be invoked. Useful when defining a new math command with \newcommand.
Print the equation number for "marker", where "marker" is the argument for a \label command in an equation.
Part of the eurosym and eurosans packages. Displays â¬.
Part of the europs package. Displays â¬.
The length of the left margin for even-numbered pages. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
Used in the "cols" argument of the begin tabular command in an @-expression. Adds additional spacing between all of the following columns.
Part of the fancybox package. Places a box around the contents of each subsequent page in the document.
Displays a frame around the text argument.
The line thickness for the \fbox and \framebox commands. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
The spacing between frame and contents in the \fbox and \framebox commands. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
Part of the color package. Draws a box around "text" contents with background color bg_color_name and line color frame_color_name.
Part of the color package. Draws a box around "text" contents with specified background and frame color. Both colors must have the same color model (e.g. "rgb").
The name given to a figure; defaults to "Figure".
A length value that defaults to zero, but can be stretched to any size.
The proportion of a float page that must be filled by floats before a new page is generated. Value is modified with the \renewcommand command.
The amount of spacing between adjacent floats. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
Add spacing between paragraphs on each page so that the final line of text is at the same position.
The \fnsymbol command causes the value of the counter to be printed in a specific sequence of nine symbols that can be used for numbering footnotes.
Sets the current font encoding.
Sets the current font family. Some values for "family" include "cmr" (Computer Modern Roman) and "cmss" (Computer Modern Sans Serif).
Sets the current font series. Some values for "series" include "m" (medium) and "bx" (bold extended).
Sets the current font shape. The "form" argument may be "n" (normal), "it" (italics), "sl" (slanted), "sc" (small caps), or "u" (unslanted italic).
Sets the current font size and line spacing.
Display "text" as a footnote.
Display "text" as a footnote. The "num" argument is the number assigned to the footnote; if omitted, footnotes are numbered sequentially.
Inserts a reference marker in the text for a footnote.
Inserts a reference marker in the text for a footnote. The "num" argument indicates which footnote is referenced.
The command for drawing the line that separates footnotes from the page content. Drawing behavior can be changed with \renewcommand.
The amount of vertical spacing between footnotes. Spacing amount is modified with the \setlength command.
Switches the font size to the value used for footnotes. Here is the ordering of font sizes: \tiny \scriptsize \footnotesize \small \normalsize (default) \large \Large \LARGE \huge \Huge

Display "text" as a footnote, without inserting a footnote reference marker into the page content. Footnotes are numbered sequentially. A reference to the footnote can be inserted into the page content with \footnotemark.

Display "text" as a footnote, without inserting a footnote reference marker into the page content. The "num" argument is the number assigned to the footnote; if omitted, footnotes are numbered sequentially. A reference to the footnote can be inserted into the page content with \footnotemark.
The minimum distance between the bottom of the text content and the bottom of the foot (the footnote area). Value is modified with the \setlength command.
Typesets "text" in the specified language.
Display a fraction in a math formula.
Place a frame around content, with no spacing between the frame border and the content.
Put a frame around text content.

Put a frame around text content. The "width" argument specifies the frame width. The "pos" argument describes text justification ("l" for left, "r" for right, "s" for fully-justified, default is center).
Put a frame around text content. The "width" and "height" arguments specify the frame dimensions.

Put a frame around text content. The "width" and "height" arguments specify the frame dimensions. The "pos" argument describes text justification ("l" for left, "r" for right, "s" for fully-justified, default is center).
Prevents additional spacing from being added to the end of each sentence. Disabled with the \nonfrenchspacing command.

In the book document class, delineates the beginning of material prior to the main book contents (table of contents, preface, etc.). Chapter numbering is disabled and pages are numbered with Roman numerals.
Disable a \sloppy command, returning inter-word spacing to normal behavior.

Displays a highly-configurable fraction in a math formula. "left" and "right" are the text that delimits the fraction on each side (e.g. parentheses). The "thickness" argument is the fraction line thickness. The "math_font_size" argument is value 0-3, or it can be empty to use the default size. "over" and "under" are the numerator and denominator, respectively.
Part of the glossary package. Define a glossary entry with the specified name and description.
Part of the glossary package. Display the glossary in the document.

Part of the graphpap package. In the picture environment, draws a grid with the lower left corner at (x, y) and the size specified by "width" and "height". The "spacing" argument is the number of units between each grid line.
The height of the head on each page. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
The spacing between the bottom of the page head and the top of the text content. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
In the letter document class, the text for the label appearing before the recipient's name; defaults to "To".
A length value reprenting the default height of a box.
The \hfill fill command produces a "rubber length" which can stretch or shrink horizontally. It will be filled with spaces.
In the array and tabular environments, produces a horizontal line across the entire width of the table.
The offset between the printer side margin and the output side margin. Value is modified with the \setlength command.
The \hrulefill fill command produces a "rubber length" which can stretch or shrink horizontally. It will be filled with a horizontal rule.
Inserts a horizontal space with the specified width. Has no effect at the beginning or end of line (use \hspace* if this is needed).
Inserts a horizontal space with the specified width.
Sets the font size. Here is the ordering of sizes: \tiny \scriptsize \footnotesize \small \normalsize (default) \large \Large \LARGE \huge \Huge
Sets the font size. Here is the ordering of sizes: \tiny \scriptsize \footnotesize \small \normalsize (default) \large \Large \LARGE \huge \Huge
Part of the hyperref package. Inserts the "text" argument as a hypertext link to target #name within the current document. The target is established with \hypertarget command.
Part of the hyperref package. Assign values to one or more of the hyperref package options.
Part of the hyperref package. Establish "text" as the target to links targeted to #name. The "text" argument may be empty for the target to refer simply to the current document location.
